I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve data from the API endpoint. This is the first step in our workflow to fetch the data we need to process.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll first execute the data_processing_validator to validate the structure of the fetched API data. Since we don't have a specific schema, I'll use a generic JSON schema validator.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array",
        "items": {
          "type": "object"
        }
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {
    "data": []
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Since the validation failed due to input format issues, I'll first execute the data_processing_parser to properly parse the raw API response before validation. This should convert the data into a valid JSON format that can be validated.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now that we have successfully parsed the API data, I'll attempt the validation again with the parsed output. I'll use a more comprehensive schema this time to ensure proper validation of the API response.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "status": {"type": "string"},
      "data": {
        "type": "array",
        "items": {
          "type": "object",
          "properties": {
            "id": {"type": "string"},
            "value": {"type": ["number", "string"]}
          },
          "required": ["id"]
        }
      },
      "timestamp": {"type": "string"}
    },
    "required": ["status", "data"]
  },
  "data": {
    "status": "success",
    "data": [],
    "timestamp": "2025-08-28T14:23:05.733766"
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
